    deviation: "Old Bay and its predecessors are seasoning agents, not flavor crutches — a Chesapeake cook applies them as a background note rather than allowing the spice blend to dominate the crab's natural sweetness. Crab cakes are bound with the absolute minimum of filler, with the regional standard demanding that lump meat remain visible as discrete pieces, never homogenized into a paste. Oysters are eaten raw, roasted over open fire, or pan-fried in cornmeal — they are rarely incorporated into composed sauces, where their identity would be lost. The preference for steaming crabs whole over boiling them is treated as a point of genuine regional pride and technical distinction.",
